Note:
HTML Parser Test Suite

Tests the HTML parser with various HTML documents.

Test Cases:
1. Basic elements - HTML5 structure with common elements
2. Lists and tables - Unordered/ordered lists, tables
3. Forms - Input elements, form attributes
4. Nested structure - Deeply nested semantic HTML
5. Comments and entities - HTML comments and entity references
6. Semantic HTML5 - Modern HTML5 semantic elements
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/html/html_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/io/file.runa" as File

@Reasoning:
Counter triple shared across the HTML parser driver. Identical layout
to the CSS/CSharp/etc. test suites so a future unified runner can
consume any of them without struct conversion.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
total at offset 0, passed at 8, failed at 16; mutated via raw
Layout.memory_set_int64 because results is shared by handle.
@End Implementation

Type called "TestResults":
    total as Integer
    passed as Integer
    failed as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Top-level driver for the HTML parser corpus. Exercises six HTML
documents covering the surface most likely to regress: basic elements,
lists/tables, forms, deeply nested DOMs, comments/entity references,
and HTML5 semantic elements. Returning 1 on any failure makes this
binary CI-friendly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Initialize TestResults, print banner, call test_parse_file once per
fixture, print summary. Return 1 if results.failed > 0 else 0.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- All six documents parse to AST with root node type 100 (HTML_DOCUMENT) -> exit 0
- Any document fails to read -> "Failed to read file" failure, exit 1
- Parser returns null on a valid file -> "Parser returned null AST", exit 1
- Root tag != 100 -> "Invalid root node type", exit 1
@End TestCases

Process called "main" returns Integer:
    Note: HTML Parser Test Suite

    Let results be a value of type TestResults with
        total as 0,
        passed as 0,
        failed as 0

    proc print_header

    Note: Test 1: Basic elements
    proc test_parse_file with "tests/translation/html/documents/basic_elements.html", results

    Note: Test 2: Lists and tables
    proc test_parse_file with "tests/translation/html/documents/lists_and_tables.html", results

    Note: Test 3: Forms
    proc test_parse_file with "tests/translation/html/documents/forms.html", results

    Note: Test 4: Nested structure
    proc test_parse_file with "tests/translation/html/documents/nested_structure.html", results

    Note: Test 5: Comments and entities
    proc test_parse_file with "tests/translation/html/documents/comments_and_entities.html", results

    Note: Test 6: Semantic HTML5
    proc test_parse_file with "tests/translation/html/documents/semantic_html5.html", results

    proc print_results from results

    If results.failed is greater than 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-document parse probe. Reads the file, runs parse_html, and verifies
the AST root tag equals 100 (HTML_DOCUMENT). Pulled into its own proc
so the counter-mutation logic lives in one place; corpus rows in main
are just path strings.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. Increment results.total.
2. read_file(file_path); null -> "Failed to read file" failure.
3. parse_html(content); null -> free content, "Parser returned null AST".
4. Verify memory_get_int64(ast, 0) == 100; otherwise free content,
   "Invalid root node type".
5. On success print [PASS], free content, increment results.passed.
@End Implementation

@TestCases:
- documents/basic_elements.html -> AST root tag 100, passed += 1
- Non-existent path -> read_file == 0 -> "Failed to read file"
- Malformed HTML -> parse_html == 0 -> "Parser returned null AST"
- Parser builds AST with non-document root -> "Invalid root node type"
@End TestCases

Process called "test_parse_file" takes file_path as Integer, results as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Test parsing an HTML file

    Let _rtot1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 0, _rtot1 plus 1

    Let content be proc read_file from File with file_path

    If content is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with file_path, "Failed to read file"
        Let _rfal1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal1 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let ast be proc parse_html from Parser with content

    If ast is equal to 0:
        proc print_test_failure with file_path, "Parser returned null AST"
        proc deallocate from Layout with content
        Let _rfal2 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal2 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with ast, 0

    If node_type is not equal to 100:
        proc print_test_failure with file_path, "Invalid root node type"
        proc deallocate from Layout with content
        Let _rfal3 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 16, _rfal3 plus 1
        Return 0
    End If

    proc print_test_success from file_path
    proc deallocate from Layout with content
    Let _rpas1 be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with results, 8
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with results, 8, _rpas1 plus 1

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Suite banner printed once at startup. Separator width (24 "=") matches
the title length so the heading lines up cleanly in CI logs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate title and "=" rule via StringCore, print each via the runtime
print primitive, then deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_header" returns Integer:
    Note: Print test suite header

    Let header be proc create_string from StringCore with "HTML Parser Test Suite"
    proc print from header
    proc deallocate from Layout with header

    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with "========================"
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits "[PASS] <path>" line. Split from print_test_failure so a grep
for "[FAIL]" on CI output cleanly isolates regressions.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[PASS] " prefix, print prefix and caller-owned file_path,
deallocate the prefix. file_path is not freed (caller-owned).
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_success" takes file_path as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Print test success message

    Let pass_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[PASS] "
    proc print from pass_msg
    proc print from file_path
    proc deallocate from Layout with pass_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Emits "[FAIL] <path>: <reason>" line. reason is one of "Failed to read
file", "Parser returned null AST", or "Invalid root node type" so the
log pinpoints the failure phase (I/O vs lex/parse vs structural check).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate "[FAIL] " prefix, print prefix/file_path/": "/reason in order,
then deallocate the prefix. file_path and reason are caller-owned.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_test_failure" takes file_path as Integer, reason as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Print test failure message

    Let fail_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "[FAIL] "
    proc print from fail_msg
    proc print from file_path
    proc print with ": "
    proc print from reason
    proc deallocate from Layout with fail_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Final summary footer. Reads counters through type-checked struct field
access (results.total etc.) at the report site even though the hot
path in test_parse_file uses raw memory_get_int64 for uniform handle
semantics.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Print "=" separator, "Test Results:" heading, then Total/Passed/Failed
lines. Each label allocated/printed/deallocated; numbers via print_int.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_results" takes results as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Print final test results

    Let separator be proc create_string from StringCore with "========================"
    proc print from separator
    proc deallocate from Layout with separator

    Let summary be proc create_string from StringCore with "Test Results:"
    proc print from summary
    proc deallocate from Layout with summary

    Let total_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Total: "
    proc print from total_msg
    proc print_int with results.total
    proc deallocate from Layout with total_msg

    Let passed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Passed: "
    proc print from passed_msg
    proc print_int with results.passed
    proc deallocate from Layout with passed_msg

    Let failed_msg be proc create_string from StringCore with "Failed: "
    proc print from failed_msg
    proc print_int with results.failed
    proc deallocate from Layout with failed_msg

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Local integer formatter (one per test file) so this suite has no
dependency on stdlib formatting allocators. Zero and negative inputs
are handled explicitly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
1. value == 0 -> print "0", return.
2. Allocate 32-byte buffer; walk position from 31 downward writing
   48 + (temp % 10), dividing temp by 10 each pass.
3. For negatives, operate on -temp and write '-' (45) at the final
   position.
4. Increment position, print buffer+position as a C string, deallocate.
@End Implementation

Process called "print_int" takes value as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Print integer value

    If value is equal to 0:
        Let zero be proc create_string from StringCore with "0"
        proc print from zero
        proc deallocate from Layout with zero
        Return 1
    End If

    Let buffer be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    Let position be 31
    Let temp be value

    If temp is less than 0:
        Set temp to -temp
    End If

    While temp is greater than 0:
        Let digit be temp modulo by 10
        Let char be 48 plus digit
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, char
        Set position to position minus 1
        Set temp to temp divided by 10
    End While

    If value is less than 0:
        proc memory_set_byte from Layout with buffer, position, 45
        Set position to position minus 1
    End If

    Set position to position plus 1
    Let str_ptr be buffer plus position
    proc print from str_ptr

    proc deallocate from Layout with buffer

    Return 1
End Process

Note: End of HTML Parser Test Suite
